<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Joint Efforts on Refugee Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Ambassador in Dhaka Saturday
suggested strong coordinated efforts by Bangladesh, Myanmar and
Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to
speed up the repatriation of the Rohingya refugees of Myanmar now
staying in camps of Bangladesh, the United News of Bangladesh (UNB)
reported.
</P>
<P>
"If coordination and cooperation among the three parties are
not in harmony, the process of repatriation cannot be speeded up,
then there will be delays," said Myanmar Ambassador in Dhaka Ohn
Thwin.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with UNB, the ambassador said his country has
already accepted more than 230,000 refugees. Out of the 7,000
cleared refugees, more than 1,500 were repatriated and another 5,
500 are in the process of scrutiny for repatriation, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Bangladesh officials, some 250,877 Rohingyas
entered the country in 1991, 20,964 of which are still awaiting
repatriation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the agreed discussions about the repatriation
among the three parties in September, 1998, the ambassador said
the people to be repatriated must be voluntary at their own will.
</P>
<P>
The issue of repatriation of Rohingya refugees was expected to
come up during the Myanmar Prime Minister Than Shwe's planned
visit to Dhaka on May 29, which was postponed due to his stated
indisposition.
</P>
<P>
Asked about any chance of rescheduling the visit sometime this
year, Thwin said the Chairman of State Peace and Development
Council of Myanmar will visit Bangladesh at a time mutually
convenient for both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
