<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slain Sri Lankan Minister, Wife Laid to Rest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A senior Sri Lankan cabinet
minister and his wife who were among 25 people killed in a Tamil
Tiger suicide bombing in Colombo's suburb earlier this week were
laid to rest Saturday evening here amid tight security and bad
weather.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Industrial Development C. V. Gunaratne and his wife
were accorded state funerals by the government of President
Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 people were also injured in the bombing on Wednesday in
the southern Ratmalana suburb, when the suicide bomber blew
himself up as the minister was leading a procession during the
first War Heroes Day to collect donations for the army.
</P>
<P>
The assassination was blamed on the rebels of Liberation Tigers
of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), who have been fighting for a separate
homeland for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since
1983.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Saturday, the procession carrying the coffins of the
minister and his wife made its way from a municipal office in a
Colombo suburb to a nearby cremation ground.
</P>
<P>
The government had tightened security for the minister's
funeral as many cabinet ministers and diplomats were present.
</P>
<P>
Only the vehicles of cabinet ministers and diplomats were
allowed closer to the funeral grounds.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people from all walks of life gathered to pay
their final tribute the minister. Some were seen weeping openly at
the grounds.
</P>
<P>
Speakers from all parties and religious dignitaries spoke of
the minister's contribution to the island nation. They said
Gunaratne worked tirelessly to bring communal harmony to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Two senior ministers read messages sent by President
Kumaratunga and Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike. The
president's message was of a personal nature. It was addressed to
the minister's children who had lost both their parents.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Saturday Kumaratunga had paid her last respect to
the slain minister when his body was brought to the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The president made her way to the Parliament by a helicopter as
security was beefed up in the capital Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Bandaranaike's message called for all Sri
Lankans to unite to defeat the fascist LTTE rebels.
</P>
<P>
A message from His Holiness the Pope condemned the
assassination of the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
