<HEADLINE> Pierce Wins French Open Singles Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Mary Pierce became the first
Frenchwoman since 1967 to win the French Open singles title by
beating Conchita Martinez 6-2, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Among a capacity crowd of about 15,000 was Francoise Durr, the
last Frenchwoman to win the title at Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
The sixth-seeded Pierce, whose only other Grand Slam title came
at the 1995 Australian Open, accepted the first-place trophy from
Martina Navratilova. Durr then kissed Pierce on both cheeks, and
the two French Open champions hugged.
</P>
<P>
Pierce, 25, has had a strained relationship in the past with
French fans, sometimes drawing jeers for lackluster play. But
they warmly embraced her this year, even though she was born in
Canada, lives in Florida and speaks with an American accent.
</P>
<P>
Pierce earned 575,000 U.S. dollars for the title while Martinez,
fifth seed, received 287,500 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the men's final Sunday, fifth-seeded Gustavo Kuerten of
Brazil will try for his second French Open title against third-
seeded Magnus Norman of Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Rule Breakers Offered Indeminity for Coming Clean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Sacked cricket captain Hansie
Cronje and disgraced team-mates Herschelle Gibbs and Henry
Williams were offered indemnity from criminal prosecution by
public prosecutor Bulelani Ngcuka if they fully disclosed their
alleged involvement in match fixing.
</P>
<P>
Sipho Ngwema, spokesman for the National Directorate of Public
Prosecutions, on Saturday said the gesture was aimed at ending
corruption in South African cricket as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We want to make sure that each person who participated in
match fixing is exposed," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Ngwema said it was hoped that the offer to Cronje, Gibbs and
Williams would result in other people possibly involved, but who
have not been called by the inquiry, being summoned to the
commission.
</P>
<P>
"The condition is that Judge Edwin King must be happy that the
testimonies (of the three) were frank and honest and that they
participated with the commission fully," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ngwema said if other individuals came forward with information,
their cases would be dealt with individually.
</P>
<P>
Cronje was axed as captain in April after admitting to taking
up to 15,000 U.S. dollars from a bookmaker for forecasting and
predicting matches.
</P>
<P>
At the time he denied match fixing allegations and approaching
his own players.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week Gibbs and Williams shocked the cricket world
when they revealed at the King Commission that Cronje offered them
15,000 dollars each, to underperform in the last one-day
international against India earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
They both accepted the offer, but neither received any money.
Gibbs claimed he forgot about the deal and went on to score 74
runs instead of the maximum of 20, while Williams left the field
injured before being able to concede 50 runs from his 10 overs.
</P>
<P>
Gibbs and Williams both face disciplinary action by the United
Cricket Board, with Gibbs already being dropped from the national
cricket team to tour Sri Lanka next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
