<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Uganda Committed to Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda and Uganda have agreed to
end their fighting in Kisangani in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC), Zambian President Frederick Chiluba said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks after he held consultation talks
 respectively with Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan
President Paul Kagame earlier Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival from Kagali, the capital of Rwanda, Chiluba
said that he was happy over the outcome of his talks with the two
leaders who reaffirmed their commitment to ceasefire in Kisangani,
the centre of diamond trade of the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who left here this morning for Uganda and then for
Rwanda, said that his mission was to find a way to implement the
Lusaka ceasefire agreement signed last year by all the parties
involved in the war, which broke in August in 1998 in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
After talks with Chiluba, Kagame said that his country is doing
every thing to see to it that the fighting, which resumed in
Kisangani last Monday, will come to an end.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the continued meeting will bear
fruit soon.
</P>
<P>
But Kagame accused Uganda of wanting his country to listen to
its order despite the fact that his country is sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that after a brief truce arranged by the United
Nations, heavy shelling between Rwandan and Ugandan forces
resumed in Kisangani, killing about 100 civilians and injuring 700
others.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda used to be allies, but now back different
rebel factions fighting in the DRC and have clashed several times
for control of Kisangani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
