<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will begin next year the construction of a power
station to be operated by solar energy and natural gas in Borg al
Arab near Alexandria on the Mediterranean coast.
</P>
<P>
The project, with a designed capacity of 1300 kilowatts/hour, is
estimated to cost 1 billion Egyptian pounds (290 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
International grants and private sector funds will cover the
cost of the power station, the construction of which will be
completed in the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Agriculture Minister Issa Kalantari and his
visiting Italian counterpart Alfonso Pecoraro Scanio here on Sunday
signed a memorandum of understanding on agricultural cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation includes training seminars in Iran and Italy for
Iranian experts and researchers on plantation and horticulture, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two sides expressed hope that the bilateral relations would
continue to expand by implementing the agreements that have already
been inked by the two countries during the visit of President
Mohammad Khatami to Italy last year.
</P>
<P>
The two officials stressed cooperation in scientific and
technical research, as well as exchange of experts and holding
short-term seminars and symposiums.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's steel exports during the first two months of
the current Iranian calendar year, which began on March 20, rose by
29 percent from those of the last year, local press on Sunday
quoted an Iranian official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Mines and Metals for Economic and
International Affairs Mohammad Taqi Ansari said that during the two
months, steel exports increased from 25.39 million U.S. dollars
last Iranian year to 32.73 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the production at the Isfahan and Khuzestan steel
complexes also surged by 100 percent and 70 percent respectively in
the period.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Abu Dhabi Development Fund on Sunday granted
Jordan two loans totalling 73.450 million Dirhams (20 million U.S.
dollars) to finance water projects.
</P>
<P>
The agreements of the 55.95 million Dirhams (15.3 million
dollars) loan to finance the construction of dams and water
pipelines in southern Jordan and the 18 million Dirhams (4.92
million dollars) loan to finance the Wihdah Dam on the Yarmouk
river were signed here Saturday between Saeed Khalfan Al Rumaithi,
Director General of the Abu Dhabi Development Fund and Eid Kamel Al
Radwan, Jordanian Ambassador to the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The loans carry an annual interest rate of three percent plus
half-a-percent in administrative cost in 20 years with a five-year
grace period, an official was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
