<HEADLINE> Egypt to Build Third Subway Line in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has planned to expand the
capital's subway network by building a third line traversing the
north of the city, the country's Middle East News Agency reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed line is designed to link Cairo International
Airport in the northeast and the Imbaba District in the northwest,
Transport Minister Ibrahim el-Demiri said after a meeting of a
working group for the project.
</P>
<P>
The line, which will be built in three phases, is estimated to
cost about 10 billion Egyptian pounds (2.9 billion U.S. dollars),
el-Demiri was quoted as saying by the news agency.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the cost will be covered by loans to be
provided by international banks and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is considering to build six more subway lines in Cairo as
it is one of the best and fastest ways to accommodate commuters,
el-Demiri added.
</P>
<P>
Cairo's existing two subway lines carry an average of 2 million
people each day, accounting for about 20 percent of the total
commuters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
