<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Export to Iraq Rise to New Level: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's exports to Iraq amounted to
392 million U.S. dollars in the past six months under the United
Nations oil-for-food program, rising to a new level, an Egyptian
assistant foreign minister said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The exports in the seventh stage of the U.N. program increased
by 82 percent compared to the previous phase, setting a record for
exports in one phase, Soliman Awad said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed economic sanctions on Iraq
after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, banning export of oil, its
main hard currency earner. But the oil-for-food deal, launched in
December 1996, allows Baghdad to sell more than billions dollars
worth of oil in every six months for buying food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The exports included equipment and raw materials worth 160
million dollars, foodstuffs worth 185 million dollars, 42 million
dollars worth of cars, and soap and industrial detergents worth 5
million dollars, Awad said, adding the private sector had the
lion's share of the exports.
</P>
<P>
The rise of the Egyptian exports to Iraq has indicated that
there are wider prospects for economic and trade cooperation
between Egypt and Iraq in the coming period, the official stressed.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad severed diplomatic relations with Cairo over Egyptian
participation in the 1991 Gulf War against Iraq's occupation of
Kuwait. But the ties have been on the mend over the past three
years, especially in the trade area, due to Egypt's weight in the
Arab world and close relations with Western countries, the United
States in particular.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian exports to Iraq have totalled 1.442 billion dollars
under the U.N. deal, making it Iraq's largest trade partner in the
Arab world and the fifth largest after Russia, China, France and
India in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
