<HEADLINE> Ugandan Troops Withdraw From Positions in Kisangani, Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The command of the Uganda People's
Defence Forces (UPDF) has taken a decision to withdraw its troops
from positions it held on June 5 in Kisangani, the Democratic
Republic of the Congo, after it reviewed the situation in the
city.
</P>
<P>
James Wapakabulo, chairman of the National Coordination
Committee on the Region, made the remarks at a press conference
here Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said: "We are now not in the town, and have withdrawn from
the Tchopo Bridge" back to Kapalata.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. observer team has taken over the bridge, and their
vehicles and U.N. flag were there, said Wapakabulo, adding: "We
hope that the Rwandan Patriotic Army will respect the U.N."
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal aims to dispel the Rwandan worldwide circulated
rumour that in spite of the understanding between Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni and Zambian President Frederick Chiluba,
the UPDF was planning an all out offensive against the Rwandan
Patriotic Army in Kisangani in order to capture the town, said
Wapakabulo.
</P>
<P>
"It is also aimed at concentrating focus on higher national,
regional and international goals enshrined in the Lusaka
Cease-fire Agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government reiterates its earlier concern that once
again the international community has allowed Rwanda to go
unpunished in spite of U.N. presence in Kisangani, a northeast
city of the DRC, said Wapakabulo.
</P>
<P>
"This will create conditions for escalation of instability in
the region, " he added.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government assures that it remains firmly
committed to the demilitarization of Kisangani and the upholding
of Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement, Wapakabulo said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda, the former two allies, have their troops
stationed in Kisangani where they have supported rival rebel
factions fighting the DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The two armies have clashed frequently since early May, and
fighting has caused heavy civilian casualties in the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
