<HEADLINE> S. African Political Parties Condemn Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- South African political
parties on Sunday joined in a chorus in condemning the bomb blast
which injured two people in Cape Town on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
The United Democratic Movement (UDM) spokeswoman for safety and
security Annelize van Wyk urged the government to take tough
measures to protect the city from bomb blasts.
</P>
<P>
What was needed was real and concerted police work, combined
with community involvement and awareness, she said.
</P>
<P>
No group has claimed responsibility for the blast which ripped
through a restaurant, wounding two people.
</P>
<P>
The Cape Peninsula has been a flashpoint of a series of bomb
blasts recently.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Party (DP) safety and security spokesman Douglas
Gibson said parliament must be briefed on Cape bombers.
</P>
<P>
He said the bombing had once again put the spotlight firmly on
the government's inability to bring to book those people
responsible for a series of bomb blasts.
</P>
<P>
Gibson said he supported the call by the DP's Western Cape
branch for the public to come forward and give police information
to assist in arresting the bombers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
