<HEADLINE> S. African Police Launch Investigation Into Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- South African police have
launched an investigation into a bomb blast which injured two
people in Cape Town on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
The shell of the red Toyota Corolla car carrying the bomb which
 detonated outside a Sea Point restaurant was taken for forensic
testing early on Sunday morning, police said.
</P>
<P>
Superintendent Riaan Pool said no one had claimed
responsibility for the blast and that there had been breakthroughs
in the investigation. He refused to give details.
</P>
<P>
Two people, an adult and a five-year-old boy, were injured in
the explosion which occurred around 7.45pm outside the New York
Bagels and Sitdown Deli Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
The victims were taken to City Park hospital. A spokeswoman at
the hospital confirmed that the two had received treatment for
hearing loss, but were not admitted.
</P>
<P>
This is the second incident of a bomb being placed in that
vicinity.
</P>
<P>
On May 22, police deactivated a pipe bomb found by two vagrants
outside the same restaurant.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town has been the scene of a spate of bombings over the
past two years in which three people have been killed and 103
injured.
</P>
<P>
The worst of these claimed the lives of two and injured 26 when
a bomb exploded inside the Planet Hollywood restaurant at the
Victoria and Alfred Waterfront last year.
</P>
<P>
In a statement in Johannesburg, the Democratic Party called for
 parliament to be briefed on the recent bombings in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
"Parliament must be informed as to what is going on. The people
of the Western Cape cannot be expected to continue living in fear,
while the criminals remain at large," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
