<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Okays Draft Law to Keep 2 Top Lebanese Guerrillas in Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli cabinet approved on
Sunday a draft law to extend the detention of two Lebanese
resistance leaders and other guerrillas who fight against Israel.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Prime Minister Ehud Barak, the cabinet decided
to table the draft legislation in the Knesset (parliament) this
week and work for its rapid enactment, the Prime Minster's Office
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister told the cabinet that Israel is obligated to
exhaust all chances to find out what happened to air force
navigator Ron Arad and other prisoners of war and those missing in
actions (MIAs), the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The two Lebanese "prisoners" are Mustafa Dirani of the Amal
movement and Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid of Hezbollah, who were held
by Israel for years as "bargaining chips" for Israeli MIAs in
Lebanon, Arad, in particular, whose jet was shot down in south
Lebanon in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the Amal movement are the two
main resistance groups fighting to oust the Israeli occupation
forces in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Judge Uri Goren of the Tel Aviv District Court said in Tel Aviv
in May that he will issue his verdict on the detention of Dirani
and Obeid on July 12 "unless the state decides to free them in the
meantime."
</P>
<P>
Dirani and Obeid appeared in open court for the first time on
May 29 to hear their case, as all previous hearings into their fate
were held behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
During the court hearing, government prosecutor Dvora Hen said
that Dirani and Obeid, two Shiite Muslim leaders whisked out of
Lebanon by Israeli commandos, pose a threat to Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
"They were major leaders of a terrorist movement and there is a
significant risk that they will resume their activities in Lebanon
once they return," Hen added.
</P>
<P>
However, Hen said, that the two men could be freed by July 17 if
Israel decided not to extend their administration detention -- a
method used by Israel to keep people in jail without charge or
trial.
</P>
<P>
"Those people have never attacked an Israeli civilian and can
not be described as terrorists," their lawyer Avi Rish stated.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government and the resistance groups such as
Hezbollah, Party of God, vowed to continue their fight unless
Israel frees all Lebanese detained by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Obeid, a former Hezbollah religious leader, was snatched by
Israeli commandos from his home in south Lebanon in 1989, while
Dirani, the former Amal security chief, was seized by Israel in
1994.
</P>
<P>
In April, the Israeli supreme court ordered the release of 13
Lebanese. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
