<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McRae Wins Acropolis Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Colin McRae won the Acropolis Rally
on Sunday after Ford team mate Carlos Sainz obeyed team orders and
yielded leadership on the final stage.
</P>
<P>
Spaniard Sainz held an advantage of more than 1-1/2 minutes
going into the closing 'Stromi-Inohori 2' run after McRae had
eased off throughout the last day to conserve his car.
</P>
<P>
Ford team bosses met both drivers on Saturday night and told
them to retain their overnight positions -- Sainz was 48.1 seconds
behind the Scot.
</P>
<P>
But Sainz stepped up the pace and finished in the top two on
the first five stages to move ahead.
</P>
<P>
McRae radioed in when he completed the final stage and Sainz
slowed to finish the world championship event in second place, 23.
1 seconds behind his teammate.
</P>
<P>
Subaru driver Juha Kankkunen was a distant third, more than six
minutes off the pace after three incident-filled days on Europe's
toughest rally.
</P>
<P>
World championship leader Richard Burns from Britain was forced
out before stage 14 after his Subaru failed to start following
turbocharger problems on the previous run while running third.
</P>
<P>
Finnish duo Makinen and Gronholm were early casualties of
Greece's unforgiving rocky terrain which allowed McRae to move
second, 14 points behind Burns in the drivers' championship.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Toshihiro Arai claimed his best world championship
finish witn fourth spot in his Subaru. Germany's Armin Schwarz
managed for a fifth spot and claimed three manufacturers' points
for Skoda.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand will host the next round of the championship on
July 13-16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
