<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Minister Visits Sri Lanka to Broker Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Indian External Affairs Minister
Jaswant Singh arrived here Sunday afternoon for talks with the Sri
Lankan President Kumaratunga and other political leaders aimed at
finding a negotiated solution to the country's long-running civil
war.
</P>
<P>
Singh is scheduled to have two rounds of talks with Sri Lankan
President Kumaratunga, officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said Singh will meet the president Sunday night at Temple
Trees, her official residence, for the first round of talks.
</P>
<P>
The Indian minister will have his second round of talks with
President Kumaratunga Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Local radio said Singh would be briefed on the latest fighting
between government troops and Tamil Tiger separatists, as well as
constitutional proposals being discussed as part of proposals to
end the civil war.
</P>
<P>
His two-day visit is also expected to calm apprehensions in
Colombo about the recent statements made by India's Tamil Nadu
Chief Minister Karunanidhi, referring to the division of Sri Lanka
as a solution to the 17-year long war between government troops
and Tamil Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
Singh is also scheduled to meet his Sri Lankan counterpart
Lakshman Kadirgamar, leader of the opposition Ranil
Wickremesinghe and leaders of all Tamil parties.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka had sought India's help when several military camps
in the northern Jaffna peninsula fell into the hands of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), who are fighting a 17-
year war to carve out a separate homeland for minority Tamils in
the island's north and east.
</P>
<P>
India, which has ruled out military involvement in the island
nation's civil war, has been in close contact with the Sri Lankan
government and promised brokering peace and humanitarian
assistance if asked.
</P>
<P>
Singh is scheduled to leave back to New Delhi Monday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
