<HEADLINE> Workshop on Space, Gene Technology Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Space, gene and state-of-the-art
computing technology was the focus of a recent workshop attended
by hundreds of top Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was sponsored by the Chinese Academy of
Engineering (CAE). Thirteen academics from CAE presented papers on
a wide ranging topics related to advanced technologies in China.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yongzhi, chief engineer of China's manned spaceflight
program, said the development and prospects of China's manned
spaceflights with the successful launch of "Shenzhou" spacecraft,
China's first experimental manned spacecraft, are encouraging.
</P>
<P>
Xu Kuangdi, a CAE member and mayor of Shanghai, presented some
new technologies on metallurgy and environmental protection. He is
very optimistic that China's iron and steel industry is capable of
taking up challenges and opportunities once China becomes a WTO
member.
</P>
<P>
Wu Mingzhu explained how she applied nuclear radiation and gene
technology to seed cultivation of Hami watermelon, one of the top
watermelon varieties in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
