<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus Minister of Commerce, Industry and Tourism
Nicos Rolandis will leave for Iran on Sunday to promote bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Rolandis is expected to hold talks with his Iranian counterpart
Mohammed Shiariatmadari and Iranian ministers of culture and oil. A
memorandum will be signed for developing cooperation in the field
of tourism.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The fourth Iranian International Fair will be held
here from June 12-16. A total of 260 local and foreign firms will
participate the fair.
</P>
<P>
The fair is jointly organized by Iranian ministry of mines and
metals, the International Exhibitions Joint Stock Company and the
German Munich International Exhibitions Company.
</P>
<P>
Products on display will include machinery and equipment for
construction industry, ceramics and natural stones processing.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's industrial sector achieved tangible
developments in l999 in terms of establishing new factories and
labor number, according to a report released by the ministry of
industry.
</P>
<P>
A total of 526 new industrial firms registered at the ministry
in l999, 16.6 percent up compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The number of labor absorbed in these firms rose 6.3 percent,
from 3,654 in l998 to 3,886 in l999, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the total invested capital of these new firms declined
from 192.9 billion liras (127 million U.S dollars) in l998 to 128.2
billion liras (80 million dollars) in 1999, said the report.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) is keen to
strengthen cooperation with Turkey, the UAE Minister of Economy and
Commerce Fahim bin Sultan Al-Qasimi said during his meeting with
the visiting Turkish business delegation.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on finding ways of expanding trade volume
between the two countries, the UAE News Agency reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
