<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Military Solution to Afghan Problem: Iranian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
here Sunday rejected war as a solution to the Afghan crisis, and
said that Iran supports peaceful means to end the bloodshed in that
country.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Afghanistan's ousted president Burhanuddin
Rabbani, Khatami stressed the need for the United Nations, the
Organization of the Islamic Conference, and the regional countries
to step up their efforts to solve the Afghan problem, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The president reiterated Iran's stance that political
negotiations should be held among different Afghan factions and
groups to form a government with the participation of all.
</P>
<P>
On the disaster of drought Afghanistan currently faces, Khatami
expressed hope that more efforts would be made to send relief
supply to the Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani, who was here for the sixth summit of the regional
Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO) held on Saturday, briefed
Khatami on latest developments in his country and cooperation among
the Northern Alliance groups which he leads against the ruling
Taliban regime.
</P>
<P>
The ousted president also called on international organizations
to help the drought-stricken people of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani's Islamic government was driven out of the capital Kabul
in 1996 by the Islamic fundamentalist Taliban militia, which now
controls more than 90 percent of the country.
</P>
<P>
Several Muslim countries have recognized the Taliban regime, but
Iran, as Afghanistan's western neighbor, still supports Rabbani.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
