<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Treasury Gestures to Avoid General Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Finance Minister Avraham
Shohat Sunday morning announced a three-week freeze on discussing a
tax reform plan, a gesture aimed to avoid a planned general strike
due to begin Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Israel Radio, Shohat called upon Amir Peretz, leader
of Histadrut, or Jewish Labor Federation, to return a favor to the
treasury's gesture, and to resume their dialog to cancel the
general strike, which will involve over 1 million unionized Israeli
workers.
</P>
<P>
In response, Peretz said he will review the gesture and consider
the possibility of calling off the strike. He also announced that
Histadrut leaders will convene Sunday night to make final decisions
on whether to carry out the work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli media reports, senior union officials said
Saturday night that if the Finance Ministry postpones
implementation of the tax reforms, the powerful labor union would
consider stopping the strike at the last minute or at least
limiting it to a shorter period of time.
</P>
<P>
The planned strike, announced last Sunday, was against the
government's tax reform plan, which was submitted by the Finance
Ministry to Prime Minister Ehud Barak last month.
</P>
<P>
The major controversial points between the union and the Finance
Ministry are the taxation of continued-education funds of average
workers, the abolishment of a half-point tax exemption for working
women and the canceling of tax breaks for shift workers in the
plan.
</P>
<P>
The planned walkout would in fact shut down the state as it will
affect all government ministries; local authorities; public
hospitals; railways, ports, and airports authorities; the state-
owned airlines, electric company, water company, telephone company,
military Industries; garbage collection; banks; universities and
more.
</P>
<P>
Essential services, such as birth and death certificates,
passports, drivers' licenses, vehicle registration renewals,
unemployment payments and services, will be halted during the
strike.
</P>
<P>
Local economists had estimated that the direct damage from the
strike will be between 600 million shekels (about 145 million U.S.
dollars) to 750 million shekels (about 181 million dollars) per day
-- an amount that will approach 1 billion (about 240 million
dollars) a day if the strike continues.
</P>
<P>
They further warned that the damage will increase as export and
import items begin spoiling at the ports, waiting for longshoremen
to handle the goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
