<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shas May Remain in Barak's Coalition: Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Labor and the religious
ultra-Orthodox Shas Party are close to reaching an agreement on the
continued participation of Shas in government, Israel Radio said on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Shas, the third largest party with 17 seats in the Knesset
(parliament), has said that if the problem of its school network is
resolved, it would agree to oppose the bill calling for the
dissolution of the 15th Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The powerful Shas party voted for the bill proposed by Knesset
Member Avigdor Lieberman in a preliminary reading on Wednesday. The
initial approval of the bill plunged the 11-month-old coalition
government led by Prime Minister Ehud Barak into an unprecedented
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Shlomo Benziri, from Shas, said all outstanding
issues must be resolved before Shas changes its position on the
early-elections bill.
</P>
<P>
Shas has been demanding millions of shekels to fund its school
system which is debt-ridden due to poor management over the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Sarid from the left-wing Meretz Party refused
to allocate more funds to that system until it improves management
and fires corrupt officials, which resulted in a serious crisis in
the coalition.
</P>
<P>
For months, Barak had invested enormous time and energy in
efforts to settle the dispute, without success. The defection of
Shas, and other two coalition partners, resulted in the passing of
the anti-government bill in the preliminary reading in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Following the defeat, Barak set out to form a new coalition.
There have been reports that he prefers a majority government to a
narrow one without the current ruling partners of Shas, the
National Religious Party and the Yisrael Ba'aliya, all of them cast
favorable votes for the bill aimed to topple the government.
</P>
<P>
A senior Shas official was quoted by the Israeli newspaper
Ha'aretz on Sunday as saying that Shas leader Eli Yishai and
Minister Haim Ramon, a right-hand man of Barak, agreed on Saturday
that Barak will not present a government with the dismissal of Shas
ministers.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the effort to prevent the ousting of Shas from
the ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
In another coalition activity, Barak's emissary and confident
Giora Eini met the anti-religious Shinui Party leader Yosef Lapid
on Saturday night to see "the possibility of Shinui joining a
government without Shas."
</P>
<P>
Sources familiar with the coalition negotiations believed that
Barak still prefers Shas over Shinui and hopes that his contacts
with Shinui would pressure Shas back into the coalition, with
increased loyalty.
</P>
<P>
Amid speculations that Barak intends to form a government
similar to the current one, Sarid said on Thursday that the Meretz
party would in no way give up the Education Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
