<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Africa Taxes 25 Percent Common Tariffs on Import Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The East African Community
(EAC) of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania have agreed to adopt a 25
percent common external tariffs to be taxed on import goods from
other parts of the world, local newspapers reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Chairman of the Tanzania Chamber of Commerce, Industries
and Agriculture Elvis Musiba told a workshop here that the three
countries reached the decision in a recent meeting in Tanzania's
northern town of Arusha where EAC Secretariat sits.
</P>
<P>
"The move is geared to protect local manufacturing industries
and agricultural produce within the region," Musiba said when
speaking at a workshop on budget process organized by the Media
Development Association (MDA) in collaboration with Conrad
Foundation and the World Bank Institute.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the main thrust now was the possibility of
the EAC members in a meeting slated for July to waive the current
internal common import tariffs from 25 percent to zero.
</P>
<P>
However, Musiba said that there were some differences among the
EAC members with Tanzania holding that the program be implemented
in a three-year period while Kenya and Uganda proposing to start
immediately.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania suggests that the internal tariffs should stand at 15
percent this year and adopt five percent tariffs next year before
settling for the zero common tariffs in 2002," he added.
"Otherwise the move is likely to disrupt the economy as Tanzania
is yet to develop its manufacturing industries compared to Kenya
and Uganda."
</P>
<P>
The EAC was founded on November 30, 1999 when Kenya, Tanzania
and Uganda signed a treaty to replace the then East African
Cooperation. The EAC will expand and deepen economic, political
and social cooperation among the three neighboring states with a
combined population of about 80 million and territories of 1.8
million square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The 153-Article Treaty for the Establishment of the East
African Community says that a Customs Union will be established as
the entry point of the Community, followed by a Common Market,
subsequently a Monetary Union and ultimately a Political
Federation of the East African States.
</P>
<P>
The main organs of the EAC are the Summit of Heads of State,
the Council of Ministers, the Coordination Committee, Sectoral
Committees, the East African Court of Justice, the East African
Legislative Assembly and the Secretariat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
