<HEADLINE> British Hooligans Arrested Face Welfare Chop, Government Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- British government warned on Sunday
that unemployed soccer fans would lose their benefits if they were
arrested at the Euro 2000 tournament.
</P>
<P>
"If people are convicted during the competition, then they are
liable to lose their benefits," Social Security Secretary Alistair
Darling told Sky Television.
</P>
<P>
The moves were part of a crackdown on welfare cheats but he
denied reports that all unemployed British fans attending the
tournament faced an end to their benefits.
</P>
<P>
"What we are concerned about is not those fans who watch
football matches and behave themselves, but those who get into
trouble," he said. "If you comply with the conditions of being on
benefit, then there is nothing to worry about." 
</P>
</TEXT>
