<HEADLINE> Mubarak Discusses Mideast Peace With Barak on Telephone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
discussed the latest developments on the Palestinian track of the
Mideast peace process early Sunday with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, Egypt's Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reviewed the latest Middle East trip by U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and issues surrounding the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, which are expected to restart next
Tuesday in the U.S., the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Albright visited Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas last
Monday and Tuesday in a fresh move to push the Mideast peace
process forward.
</P>
<P>
Palestine and Israel have been working to reach a framework
agreement for a final peace treaty by September on the thorniest
issues of Jerusalem, borders, settlements, refugees and water.
</P>
<P>
During the telephone conversation, Barak also expressed
condolences on the passing of Syrian President Hafez al-Assad,
adding that Israel is keen to realize a "comprehensive and just"
peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Assad died of heart attack Saturday, Israel said
in a statement that it understood the grief of the Syrian people
and will continue to work for a peace agreement with Syria's
succeeding leadership.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between the two foes were halted last January after
Israel refused to promise in advance a full return of the Golan
Heights it captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.  
</P>
</TEXT>
