<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Shock As Tories Close Poll Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 11 (Xinhua) - A new opinion poll published Sunday
puts the Tories just three points behind Labor. The astonishing
figure is the closest the Tories have been to Labor for nearly
eight years.
</P>
<P>
It shows Labor on 41 points with the Tories on 38. The Labor
government's ratings have fallen by five points in just three
weeks and a staggering 21 since their peak in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
Just over a year ago, 53 percent saw Tony Blair as the most
capable Prime Minister, now that figure is 37. Meanwhile,
Opposition leader Hague's score has doubled from just nine percent
to 18.
</P>
<P>
The MORI poll was carried out in the two days after the Prime
Minister was heckled by the Women's Institute - Tony Blair's worst
day since he came to power.
</P>
<P>
Bob Worcester, head of MORI, said: "The crack in the facade
exposed by the Women's Institute at Wembley has resonated with the
public."
</P>
<P>
He said he expected Labor's lead to bounce back to seven to 10
percent when the "WI effect" wore off and he still expected Labor
to win the next election.
</P>
<P>
However, the MORI survey contained a serious warning for the
Labor Government. Worcester said, voters see Labor as a government
of spin rather than a government of delivery.
</P>
<P>
"If the Opposition was stronger, Blair would be in dead trouble,
" he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
