<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish FM Starts Trip to Central Asia to Assert Influence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
is to make a diplomatic offensive in Central Asia, in an effort to
check Russian influence and assert Turkey's "pivotal" role in the
region.
</P>
<P>
His tour of Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan will begin on Sunday,
according to local media.
</P>
<P>
This move came amid mounting criticism in Turkey of his foreign
policy, which is seen as too leaning toward Europe while ignoring
what Turkey called "Turkic-speaking states" in Central Asia and
Caucasia.
</P>
<P>
Five countries in the region gained independence after the
collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991. Turkey believes most of those
republics have traditional, geographical and cultural ties with it,
and has been trying to expand its influence in those countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey eyes Russia as a rival vying for control of the region.
Russian President Vladimir Putin visited Turkmenistan and
Uzbekistan last month to strengthen ties with the two former Soviet
republics.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Russia signed a deal to increase natural gas
purchase from Turkmenistan, which set alarm to Turkey, the U.S. and
Europe as to Moscow's attempt to reassert its presence in its
traditional sphere of influence. 
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan suspended gas supplies to Russia after a dispute
over debts, but resumed them this year for a total of 20 billion
cubic meters (700 billion cubic feet). 
</P>
<P>
The latest Russia-Turkmenistan agreement could pose threat to a
U.S.-backed plan to build a gas pipeline from Turkmenistan to
Turkey via the Caspian Sea, as so much gas would be transferred to
Russia instead.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that during his visit, Cem will discuss with
leaders of the two countries bilateral and regional issues, energy
cooperation in particular.
</P>
<P>
In an extraordinary luncheon he hosted for the ambassadors of
Central Asian and Caucasian republics at his residence late last
month, Cem declared that Eurasia had "very, very important" place
in Turkey's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
To be a "pivotal player" in Eurasian politics, and to become a
full member of the European Union, are two topping priorities of
Turkey's foreign policy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was granted candidacy for membership of the 15-member
European rich-nation club last December after years of strenuous
efforts. But Cem came under fire for his ministry's "too much"
preoccupation with its relations with Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
