<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tourism, Both Boon and Bane to Nepal by Zhuang Meijie, Song Dejun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- While a great influx of foreign
tourists brought to Nepal the much-coveted dollars, they have also
incurred unwanted changes to the otherwise pristine Himalayan
kingdom boasting of unique tradition, culture and ecology.
</P>
<P>
Contributing 24 percent to the country's foreign exchange
income, Nepal's tourism industry is recognized as an important
sector for the upliftment of the country's economy, one of the
least developed economies in the world.
</P>
<P>
With 500,000 tourists coming each year, tourism is providing
jobs to 200,000 Nepali people, accounting for one sixteenths of
the employed in the country.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic benefits, the tourism has also brought
about some adverse effects, including socio-cultural degradation,
malpractice like drug abuse, child abuse, increasing crimes and
social turbulence, according to a survey conducted recently by
kathmandu University.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that about 40 percent of the respondents felt
that tourism is responsible for deterioration of social values and
changing culture, as unethical behaviors and ideas of some of the
tourists are indenting local traditions and cultures in a
imperceptible way.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of the respondents said foreign tourists are
the main cause for the sharp increase of drug abuse among
youngsters, who are allured to imitate foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Criminal cases, such as pickpocketing, fighting, robbery and
even killing, are also on the rise in recent years, said the
survey.
</P>
<P>
"Though crimes in Nepal are much fewer comparing to
metropolitans like New York, they terrify people who are used to
peaceful life and make inroads on our social values," said Dhruba
Adhikary, professor with Nepal Press Institute.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the development of tourism has caused
environmental degradation and threatens the fragile ecology in the
mountainous country.
</P>
<P>
Being the juncture of eastern and western Himalayas, Nepal
possesses a wide range of floral and faunal diversity and boasts
of untouched forests and two natural conservation -- Chitwan and
Qomolangma (also called Everest or Sagarmatha) parks, listed by
UNESCO (U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization) as
world heritage.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has also recorded about 75 vegetation types, over 6000
species of flowering plants and ferns, 181 species of fauna and
844 species of birds. But as a result of mountain tourism,
increased demand for fuelwood and timber, increased pollution and
generation of bio-non-degradable garbage as well as lodge
constructions and changes in land use are posing serious threat to
the mountain ecology, according to a recent research.
</P>
<P>
The research conducted by ICIMOD (International Center for
Integrated Mountain Development) showed that 9.2 metric tons of
fuelwood was consumed daily by the lodges in the Qomolangma region
alone. At this speed, forests in the region will be destroyed
within years.
</P>
<P>
"As of 1999, there were 20 settlements in the Qomolangma region
and 43 in the Annapurna region as a result of tourism," said Dr.
Pitamber Sharma with ICIMOD.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, large amount of solid waste left by trekkers and
generated in the lodges are posing alarming environmental problems
and turning scenic trekking areas into dustbins.
</P>
<P>
In view of all these problems, to keep balance between
promoting sustainable tourism and conserving the fragile ecology
is becoming a big challenge for the Nepali government and tourism
entrepreneurs, the research said in conclusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
