<HEADLINE> Kenya to Waive Duty on Diesel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is
considering waiving import duty on diesel for the next six
months, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi has said.
</P>
<P>
Moi said Saturday in Nakuru city in central Kenya that the
intended waiver was expected to minimize the effect of the power
shortage, which threatens 300,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The step is to make the fuel affordable during the power
rationing period, the Sunday Standard newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is experiencing a long-spell severe drought nationwide,
which has lead to lowest water levels of major energy reservoirs
affecting the power generation, leaving an electricity shortfall
of between 154 and 360 kilowatts in the off-peak and peak hours
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Due to the introduction of a stricter power rationing by the
government from the beginning of June, diesel is in great demand
by various institutions which have their own power generators.
</P>
</TEXT>
