<HEADLINE> Nigerian Ruling Party Slams Fuel Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian ruling People's Democratic
Party Saturday criticized the government's decision to raise up
the petrol price, saying that the procedure, timing and margins
of the increase were wrong.
</P>
<P>
Short of blaming President Olusegun Obasanjo for unilaterally
effecting the price increase, the party, which spoke through its
National Publicity Secretary, Emmanuel Ibeshi in Abuja, deplored
that the increase was not based on consultation.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian press Sunday quoted him as saying that the new price
regime could not align with the masses's acceptability for such a
hike.
</P>
<P>
He called up the government to restore the price to old level
and make consultations in the future before making such decisions
with national implications.
</P>
<P>
The party also urges the labor to stop the strike and resume
work on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The country's umbrella labor organization the National Labor
Congress (NLC) launched the ongoing strike shortly after the
Nigerian government increased the country's petrol price by 50
percent to 30 naira per liter (one U. S. dollar is equal to 100
naira) on June 1.
</P>
<P>
Several people have been reportedly killed, and more wounded in
violence relating to the strike in the last two days. Police have
reportedly arrested hundreds of rioters.
</P>
<P>
Governments at federal and state levels have remained closed
since the start of the strike.
</P>
<P>
The NLC refused to call off the strike, in spite of the fact
that the government last Thursday had announced
five-naira-per-liter reductions for petrol and diesel, and
10-naira-per-liter reduction for kerosine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
