<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Iran's New Parliamentary Speaker Mehdi Karrubi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Mehdi Karrubi, a prominent radical-
turned reformist leader, was elected on Sunday speaker of Iran's
sixth Majlis (parliament) dominated by reformists allied with
President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for Karrubi, 63, to hold the post. He
had been elected as Majlis speaker in 1989. But three years later,
he not only lost the speakership, but also even a seat in the
legislature in the fourth parliamentary elections in 1992, due to
conservative pressures.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi was a member of the first, second and third Majlis. He
was elected vice speaker in the second Majlis, and then took the
post of speaker in 1989 after the then speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani
was elected president.
</P>
<P>
However, he came under fierce criticism from the rightist or
conservative camp and the centralist or moderate camp led by
Rafsanjani, and was ousted with his radical allies from the
parliament in the fourth parliamentary elections in 1992 after
Rafsanjani joined hands with the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi and his allies threw their support behind Mohammad
Khatami, a moderate in the radical Assembly of Combatant Clergy
(ACC) Central Council, in the 1997 presidential election. Khatami
defeated the powerful conservative candidate, former Majlis Speaker
Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri, by a landslide.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi and his allies support the reformist programs of
President Khatami, but distanced themselves from the newly-grown
reformist camp led by the president's younger brother Mohammad Reza
Khatami and freedom-seeking students.
</P>
<P>
Before the 1979 Islamic revolution, Karrubi had been a radical
leader in the Islamic movement led by late spiritual leader
Ayatollah Musavi Khomeini. He was arrested several times by the
late shah's police and spent four years in prison and a while in
exile.
</P>
<P>
After Khomeini took power in the Islamic revolution, Karrubi
first headed the Imam Khomeini Relief Committee in Tehran, and then
the Martyrs Foundation from 1980-1993.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi obtained a B.A. in divinity and philosophy from Tehran
University and completed seminary studies with a religious title of
Hojatoleslam as confirmed by some religious jurisprudents.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi is a father of four. His wife, Fatemeh, was a member of
the conservative-dominated fifth Majlis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singh's Visit to Sri Lanka Expected: Sri Lankan Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- India's External Affairs Minister
Jaswant Singh's visit to Sri Lanka is not sudden but expected and
the two countries have been working on it for some time, a senior
official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Romesh Jayasinghe, director general of South Asia in Sri Lanka'
s Ministry of Foreign Affairs, told Xinhua that Singh's visit to
the island country Sunday afternoon is "a step in a process and
there was no urgency in his visit," dismissing some predictions
that Singh's visit is a matter of urgency.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the situation has stabilized in the northern
Jaffna peninsula where government troops have been battling an
offensive by the separatist Tamil Tiger rebels since April.
</P>
<P>
Singh's visit is the first high level one by the Indian
government since April when the civil war in Sri Lanka flared up
between government troops and Tamil Tiger rebels who are fighting
a 17-year war to carve out a separate homeland for minority Tamils
in the island's north and east.
</P>
<P>
India, which has ruled out military involvement in the island
nation's civil war, has been in close contact with the Sri Lankan
government and promised humanitarian assistance if asked.
</P>
<P>
Singh is expected to have talks with his Sri Lankan counterpart
Lakshman Kadirgamar and President Chandrika Kumaratunga on the
current developments in the country's civil war and peace
prospects, before he leaves for New Delhi Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
His visit is also expected to calm apprehensions in Colombo
about the recent statements made by India's Tamil Nadu Chief
Minister Karunanidhi, referring to the division of Sri Lanka as a
solution to the 17-year long ethnic conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
