<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States Takes Pacific Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- the United States sealed the
winner of the inaugural Pacific Cup women's soccer tournament on
Sunday by beating Australia 1-0 in Newcastle, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Although tied with China and Canada on 12 points, a superior
goal difference gave the World Cup-champion Americans the triumph
in the six-nation international competition, accroding to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Australia finished in fourth place on nine points, followed by
Japan and winless New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The United States created the best chances, the first as early
as the fourth minute when 200-game veteran Kristine Lilly shot
wide.
</P>
<P>
Australian striker Sunni Hughes broke into the U.S. penalty
area in the 13th minute and went down under a heavy challenge but
the referee ignored a plea for a penalty.
</P>
<P>
Australian goalkeeper Tracey Wheeler had to be at her best,
producing a great double save to deny U.S. midfielder Tiffeny
Milbrett on 20 minutes and moments later Milbrett squandered a
chance, shooting wide when in scoring range.
</P>
<P>
Australia created a half chance in the 57th minute when Hughes
was released behind the U.S. defense, but goalkeeper Siry Mullinix
was quickly out of her area to clear.
</P>
<P>
The winner came after Australian defender Cheryl Salisbury
played at the ball with her arm under pressure from American
substitute striker Cindy Parlow. Shannon MacMillan took the
penalty and calmly sent Wheeler the wrong way.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Torrential Rain Suspends Transportation on South China River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Transportation on China's Lijiang
River in Guilin, a well-known tourist city in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, was suspended today due to
severe flooding resulting from days of torrential rain.
</P>
<P>
This is the first ban on transportation on Lijiang this year.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain began to hit Guilin on June 6 and by 08:00 this
morning, the rainfall had reached 343 millimeters.
</P>
<P>
The water level on the river rose to 144.88 meters, only 0.12
meters below the warning stage.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the local transportation department said effective
measures are being taken to evacuate the 3,070 tourists on the
river, including 770 foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that as the water level is declining today,
the transportation ban is expected to be lifted tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
However, local meteorologists forecast more torrential rains
for June 15 and 19.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
