<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karrubi Elected Iranian Majlis Speaker EDS-Retransmitting to fix seventh para </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran's new, reformist-dominated
Majlis (parliament) on Sunday elected Mehdi Karrubi, a prominent
radical-turned reformist leader, as its speaker for a one-year
term.
</P>
<P>
Behzad Nabavi, spokesman of the reformist coalition "May 23
Front," and Mohammad Reza Khatami, the younger brother of President
Mohammad Khatami, were elected vice speakers.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi, as the only candidate for the post, won 193 votes out
of a total of 245, with 52 abstentions, in the election of the
Majlis presiding board.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's open session of the Majlis was broadcast live by Iran's
state-run radio.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi was elected provisional speaker on May 30, taking charge
of the Majlis to screen credentials of the elected lawmakers. He
won 186 votes out of a total of 249 with 63 abstentions in that
balloting.
</P>
<P>
According to Iranian law, the new speaker should be elected only
after credentials of two thirds of the elected parliamentarians
have been approved by the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
The new Majlis, in which the reformists secured a two-third
majority, was sworn in on May 27, putting an end to conservative
dominance.
</P>
<P>
Karrubi, 63, had been elected in 1989 as Majlis speaker. But
three yeas later he not only lost the speakership, but also even a
seat in the legislature in the fourth parliamentary elections in
1992, due to conservative pressures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
