<HEADLINE> Zambian Police Ordered to Shoot Armed Bandits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police have been ordered to
shoot armed bandits, as the southern African country intensified
its fighting against crimes, Sunday Times of Zambia newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
In line with the orders which come alongside intensified
patrols in townships at night, armed bandits will be shot when
they use firearms.
</P>
<P>
According to Lusaka police chief Bernard Mayonda, armed
banditry would no longer be tolerated and any armed bandits would
be met with fire and their chances of survival were nil.
</P>
<P>
"My officers have been given specific instructions to respond
to fire with fire, this is not a threat but it is imperative that
we respond to each situation as it comes," Mayonda was quoted by
the newspaper as saying on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
And while the guns amnesty is being intensified to ensure as
many illegal firearms as possible are recovered, the police will
crack down heavily on all those who are found in possession of
such firearms.
</P>
<P>
According to the Lusaka police chief, the crime wave in Lusaka
is now under manageable levels with the number of car thefts
having dropped from the previous three per day to just one.
</P>
<P>
Appealing for increased cooperation and information from the
public, Mayonda stressed the importance of neighborhood watch
schemes in the fight against crime.
</P>
<P>
And to facilitate this officers in charge of police stations
have been directed to strengthen their cooperation with
neighborhood watch schemes in their respective areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
