<HEADLINE> Famine Claims 10 More Lives in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 people have died of
hunger in various parts of Kenya, the Sunday Nation newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Among the dead, including three children aged between two and
five died in the past two weeks in Dukana location of Marsabit
District in northern Kenya and two others in Laikipia District in
central Kenya, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Severe famine has gripped many parts of Kenya due to the
prolonged drought, affecting 23 million Kenyans, about 80 percent
of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi appealed to the
 international community for emergency food aid to almost three
million Kenyans who are absolutely destitute hit by drought.
</P>
<P>
Moi said at least 11.5 billion shillings (some 150 million U.S.
dollars) is needed to combat the famine, of which food will take
85 percent.
</P>
<P>
So far, the international community, U.N. agencies and
non-governmental organizations have reacted positively to Moi's
urgent appeal for relief food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
