<HEADLINE> Slight Earthquake Occurs in Myanmar Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake of slight intensity
measuring 2.8 on the Richter scale shook the capital of Yangon
Saturday, according to the country's Seismological Observatory.
</P>
<P>
The quake, the 4th of a series of earthquakes hitting Myanmar
in the last few days, occurred at 01 hour 03 minutes 14 seconds
local time with a duration of two seconds and its epicenter was
about 16.8 kilometers south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
In the previous two days, three moderate earthquakes measuring
6.5, 5.6 and 5.1 respectively on the Richter scale, jolted Myanmar
's northern Kachin state successively.
</P>
<P>
The epicenters of the first and second quakes which occurred on
Thursday was about 1,156 kilometers (km) and 1,211 km north of the
capital respectively, while that of the third quake which took
place on Friday was about 1,012 km northeast of Yangon.
</P>
<P>
So far, there were no immediate reports of casualties and
damage for the four quakes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
