<HEADLINE> Thailand Won't Repay IMF Loan Before Schedule: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will not start
to repay the bailout loan it received from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) during the economic crisis before schedule,
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai was quoted by Thai News Agency as
saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The government had yet talked about the issue, but had decided
to stop to withdraw further funds from the IMF's rescue package,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is scheduled to repay the bailout loan to the IMF next
year, according to him.
</P>
<P>
Thailand accepted a bailout loan of 17.2 billion U.S. dollars
from the Washington-based institute when the country fell into its
worst economic turmoil in mid 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government has, however, withdrawn about 12 billion dollars
from the rescue package, as the country's official reserves have
increased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
