<HEADLINE> Death Toll Hits 25 in Police-Guerrillas Clash in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in the police-
guerrillas clash that raged on till Saturday in Jajarkot district
of mid-western Nepal had reached 25, including 12 policemen, seven
civilians and six guerrillas, The Kathmandu Post reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Five children and one woman were among the killed in the fierce
fighting that broke out on Thursday when some 1,600 guerrillas
attacked a police post in a remote village in Jajarkot district,
the English daily said.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas managed to capture the post after the policemen
ran out of munitions, said Bajgain.
</P>
<P>
Among the 51 policemen and two cooks stationed at the police
post, at least 36 were injured, some of them in critical condition,
according to police sources.
</P>
<P>
The seven villagers, including five children, died a violent
death while some were injured when guerrillas attacked their hut
where some policemen had sought shelter, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Police dispatched for rescue operation have not reached the
site owing to incessant rains and thick fog, they said.
</P>
<P>
The clash in Jajarkot is one of the bloodiest battles since the
guerrillas began armed activities in 1996. At least 1,300 people,
including police, guerrillas and civilians, have lost their lives
in guerrillas related clashes with police during the four years.
</P>
</TEXT>
