<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Top General Vows to Prevent Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Army's chief of staff,
General Nebojsa Pavkovic, on Saturday condemned NATO's aggression
against his country last year and warned that his troops will "
prevent civil war at any cost."
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony in Aleksinac, a small city in eastern Yugoslavia,
to mark the first anniversary of the ending of NATO aggression,
Pavkovic said the Yugoslav army is "the army of the people" and
will prevent civil war at any cost and resolutely defend the
homeland and the people.
</P>
<P>
Pavkovic said the U.S.-led NATO continued to sabotage
Yugoslavia after it ended its bombing a year ago.
</P>
<P>
NATO has been trying to overthrow the Yugoslav government by
instigating sabotage by antagonized forces in the country and by
fomenting discord between the two republics, Serbia and Montenegro,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The army ... is united, firm and combat-ready to prevent any
secessionist scenarios."
</P>
<P>
NATO, in disregard of Resolution 1244 of the U.N. Security
Council, connived at the ethnic cleansing by Kosovo Albanian
extremists, said the general.
</P>
<P>
He praised the army for its outstanding performance in
safeguarding the country's sovereignty, independence and
constitutional order in last year's fight against NATO aggression.
The army will continue to honor its constitutional commitments in
case of need, he said.
</P>
<P>
During NATO's 78-day air strikes ended on June 10, 1999,
Aleksinac was hit on seven occasions, including an attack on an
apartment complex that killed 17 civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
