<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- China's Tibet Autonomous Region plans to launch 1,350
projects involving a total investment of 206.7 billion yuan (about
24.9 billion U.S. dollars) as part of a national effort to develop
the country's western areas.
</P>
<P>
-- The Red Cross Society of China Saturday offered 20,000 U.S.
dollars of aid to the Red Cross Society of Indonesia to help
rebuild homes of Indonesians who suffered from a recent earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, measuring 7.9 on the Richter scale, hit the
Indonesian island of Sumatra last Sunday, resulting in massive
casualties and property damage.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- The Seventh China-ROK Forum on Future Development opened
Saturday in the municipality of Chongqing in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, participants from China and the
Republic of Korea (ROK) will discuss development in northeast Asia
and bilateral economic and trade cooperation as it relates to
China's strategy of developing its western regions.
</P>
<P>
-- China announced its top 50 listed companies Saturday,
including Shanghai Petrochemicals, Changhong, and Pudong
Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- China will take measures to improve auditing of the social
security system to close loopholes in fund accounts and strengthen
its pension system reform this year.
</P>
<P>
Li Jinhua, general director of China National Audit Office,
said the country will investigate 71 enterprises which have
seriously delayed payments to pension insurance accounts, while
probing pension fund misuse in seven provinces.
</P>
<P>
-- Despite strained political relations across the Taiwan
Straits, trade and investment volumes between the two sides have
expanded remarkably and are believed to be gathering momentum.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the General Administration of Customs indicate
that cross-Straits trade increased a year-on-year 30.4 percent to
reach 8.71 billion U.S. dollars during the first four months of
the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
