<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Tremors Rock Indonesia's Bengkulu Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Three more earthquakes, measuring
between 4.9 and 6 on the Richter Scale, struck Bengkulu on
Saturday, according to the National Meteorology and Geophysics
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The first quake hit the area at 01:32 a.m. local time with a
magnitude of 4.9 on the Richter Scale.
</P>
<P>
The strongest tremor jolted Bengkulu province at 05:00 a.m.
local time. The epicenter was located 253 kilometers southwest of
Bengkulu, some 74 kilometers below the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The third tremor hit at 12:11 p.m. local time, measuring 5.5 on
the Richter Scale.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake was also felt in the Sumatran cities of Padang,
Jambi, Palembang and Lampung, and in Singapore, the agency
spokesman Waan Tarmin was quoted by the Jakarta Post Sunday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
By Saturday, more than 750 aftershocks had been recorded since
the devastating 7.9 earthquake devastated the province on Sunday
night. At least 133 persons died in the quake.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that residents' frustration over the perceived
slow government reaction to the quake victims' plight boiled over
on Saturday when occupants of a residential area in Bengkulu
forced Coordinating Minister for Political Affairs and Security
Surjadi Soedirdja and Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare
Basri Hasanuddin to inspect the damage to their houses.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputri, whose mother Fatmawati
was from Bengkulu, will visit the province on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
