<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Bans Non-degradable Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Starting July 1, northeast China'
s Liaoning Province will ban plastic tableware to cut back on the
pollution produced by such non-degradable products.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, bio-degradable materials such as paper, plant fiber,
and starch are officially recommended to replace plastics for
making tableware and degradable plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
About one billion sets of plastic tableware and more than 100,
000 tons of plastic bags are sold in Liaoning annually, accounting
for one tenth of the nation's total. These plastic items seriously
threaten the local environment, since it will take about 200 years
for them to degrade.
</P>
<P>
Environmental problems created by randomly-discarded plastic
products are blamed for China's "white pollution" woes. About a
dozen Chinese municipalities, provinces and autonomous regions are
introducing similar bans on non-degradable products.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 enterprises in Liaoning have passed a review and
been authorized to produce bio-degradable tableware and plastic
bags. Products from enterprises outside Liaoning are banned from
sale in the province without official authorization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mosuo People Maintain Rare Matriarchal Society (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guests living in the compound find the Mosuo lifestyle
fascinating. At night, tourists gather around a fire in the center
of the courtyard to watch Mosuo youth perform ethnic songs and
dances.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has become so profitable that many Mosuo families in
the area who have opened their homes have become wealthy.
Caoshidamu's family has a color TV, stereo, washing machine, and
lots of other modern household conveniences.
</P>
<P>
But they have no plans to relinquish their ties to the ancient
matriarchal system, which is rare in the world.
</P>
<P>
In Mosuo tradition, only daughters can be heirs in a family.
Caoshidamu pays close attention to the healthy growth of the
younger generation in the family, particularly the daughters. Now
all three of her daughters are in school.
</P>
<P>
And Mosuos also have preserved the unusual system of live-apart
marriages. In the Mosuo world, wives and husbands live separately,
in their mothers' homes, during the day, and are permitted to meet
only at night.
</P>
<P>
Curious tourists like to ask about this unique arrangement, and
Mosuos don't shy away from answering intimate details about their
marriages.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen-year-old Arzhou says happily, "My mother has agreed
to let me have such a man to meet beginning from next year."
</P>
<P>
Arzhuo, who lives in a Mosuo courtyard only ten meters from the
lake, rows tourist-filled canoes on the serene water every day.
</P>
<P>
Shi Run, a postgraduate student at Yunnan University who is
conducting research on the Mosuo people, said that Mosuo families
in the villages of Lugu Lake area represent one of the world's
best-preserved matriarchal societies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mosuo People Maintain Rare Matriarchal Society (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A matriarchal community in
southwest China has held fast to its traditions despite being
buffeted by the tides of economic development and modern
civilization.
</P>
<P>
The 30,000 people of the Mosuo minority continue to live in
their generations-old wood-frame houses which ring the 60-sq-km
Lugu lake separating southwest China's Sichuan and Yunnan
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Caoshidamu, 38, who is second-in-command of one of the Mosuo
families, has opened an inn for tourists in the residential
compound where she lives, just ten meters away from Lugu Lake.
</P>
<P>
Inside the compound are scripture halls, a central gathering
room, and women's bedrooms. The rest of the family -- the men --
occupy other rooms in the quadrangle, and extra rooms are used for
the steady stream of tourists.
</P>
<P>
Caoshidamu's 71-year-old mother is the highest-ranking
authority of their 11-member family, but Caoshidamu actually runs
day-to-day operations, assigning her brothers and sisters chores
such as catching fish and shrimp from the lake to use for
preparing traditional Mosuo meals for tourists.
</P>
<P>
Since the area opened to the outside in 1988, Lugu Lake has
turned into a destination for international visitors lured by its
crystal clear water high in a spectacular mountain environment.
</P>
<P>
Living at an elevation of 3,000 meters, the Mosuo people have
historically existed on fishing, farming and herding. But the
influx of tourists has given the Mosuos the chance to see what's
what with the outside world, and has created a new and welcome
source of income.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Helps Disabled Find Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Of China's 60 million disabled
people, 75 percent have obtained jobs, and the Chinese government
pledges to raise their employment rate to 85 percent in five years,
sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The central authorities has formulated a number of laws and
regulations to protect the rights of the disabled. Some 5,000
employment centers have been set up across the country to improve
their living standards, said Wang Chenjing, an official with the
China Association for the Handicapped.
</P>
<P>
As the nation's unemployment rate has continued to grow in
recent years, disabled people have faced their own challenges. To
encourage them to start their own businesses, the Chinese
government has offered tax holidays.
</P>
<P>
Tan Ping, a disabled woman in Dingxi County in northwest China'
s Gansu Province, started her own fruit-selling business, which
has become so profitable she can now live comfortably on her
earnings.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show there are 1.2 million self-employed disabled
people in the country, 12 times the number a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Li Baohu in Zhengning County is another example. The local
government gave the disabled youth 1,000 yuan to open a private
clinic when he graduated from a medical school. His business has
been successful, and now he lives an independent life.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, many organizations have been set up to offer
employment information, vocational training and insurance services
for disabled people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights
of major environment news stories Xinhua released from June 3 to
10:
</P>
<P>
China Curbs Worsening of Environment
</P>
<P>
China has managed to prevent the natural environment from
worsening with environmental situation improving in many parts of
the country, according to an official report.
</P>
<P>
The report, titled "China Environmental Situation Bulletin
1999", also warned that the overall environmental situation in
China remains rather serious as the total volume of pollutants
discharged across the country stays high.
</P>
<P>
China to Step Up Fight Against Agriculture Pollution
</P>
<P>
China is preparing to fight the country's worsening
agricultural environment so that sustained developments in rural
areas can become a reality, Vice Minister of Agriculture Zhang
Baowen said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 130,000 hectares of farmland
have been damaged by industrial solid waste, and over 5.3 million
hectares of land are affected by air pollution.
</P>
<P>
China's Major Rivers, Lakes Remain Polluted
</P>
<P>
China said Monday most of its major rivers and lakes remained
seriously polluted last year despite a nationwide campaign to cut
water pollution in the past years.
</P>
<P>
To curb the worsening water pollution, China has closed tens
of thousands of small and medium-sized polluting firms in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Polluting Firms Facing Shut Down: Official
</P>
<P>
Some 7,000 polluting firms will be closed if they fail to meet
the official pollutant discharge requirements by the end of this
year, Xie Zhenhua, director of the State Environmental Protection
Administration (SEPA), issued the ultimatum at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government decided in 1996 that all polluting firms
must meet pollutant discharge standards by the end of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More Chinese Keen on Environmental Reports
</P>
<P>
A number of Chinese provinces and cities, such as Shenzhen and
Shanghai, published local environmental reports to mark the World
Environment Day, designated as the day to expose global concerns
about environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, which came first in the comprehensive assessment of
environment situation among 46 major cities in China last year,
released a comprehensive environmental situation bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The city pooled 2.6 billion yuan for its environmental
protection programs in 1999, which accounted for 1.85 percent of
its GDP for the year, higher than the national average of one
percent.
</P>
<P>
China Releases First Ozone Exploration Balloon
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists sent up the country's first ozone
exploration balloon on the northern slope of Mount Qomolangma,
better known in the West as Mt. Everest, to detect the ozone
density around the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau in summer.
</P>
<P>
When the grey balloon reached an altitude of 20-30 km above the
ground surface, a sensor attached to the balloon began to transmit
scientific data, which will aid the study of ozone distribution in
the atmosphere of the plateau.
</P>
<P>
Paper Recycling Program Launched in Beijing
</P>
<P>
China launched a paper-recycling program, targeting government
and institutional offices and commercial buildings as part of the
effort to encourage the environment-friendly use of paper.
</P>
<P>
The program was kicked off by the Publicity and Education
Center of the State Environment Protection Administration (SEPA)
and the Beijing Municipal Administrating Committee in cooperation
with Exxon Mobil China Environmental Education Fund.
</P>
<P>
Hubei Initiates Plan to Clean up Lakes, Rivers
</P>
<P>
Central China's Hubei Province have been carrying out a 229
million U.S. dollar program under which World Bank loans are used
to improve the quality of water in six local lakes and rivers.
</P>
<P>
Hubei, dubbed as a "province with 1,000 lakes", abounds in
water resources. But the quality of water in most lakes and
rivers has been worsening as a result of random discharge of
sewage and industrial waste water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A comprehensive environment protection project in east China's
Jiangxi Province had been shown at the Expo 2000, which started on
June 1 in Germany's Hanover.
</P>
<P>
The project commenced in 1983 and covers nearly 120,000 sq km,
including mountainous areas, the valley of the local Ganjiang
River and the areas of the Poyang Lake, China's largest freshwater
lake.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Reports Initial Success in Water Pollution Reduction
</P>
<P>
Pollution has been controlled in the water system of the Liaohe
River in northeast China's Liaoning Province, with 70 percent of
the polluting enterprises in the area meeting pollution control
standards and 11 water treatment plants either completed or under
construction.
</P>
<P>
As the most polluted of the three rivers earmarked by the
central government in its pollution-control campaign, Liaohe River
has received special attention since last March when the State
Council approved a draft governing pollution control in the river.
</P>
<P>
Red Tide Hits South China Sea
</P>
<P>
A red tide was spotted in the sea off Nan'ao County, in
Guangdong Province, around 15:40 hours Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nanhai Branch of the State Oceanic Administration said the red
tide first occurred at 10:00 hours Wednesday and extended four
meters in width around 15:00 hours. The russet belt mainly
consists of luminous algae, which produces no toxins, but the
outbreak of the red tide is detrimental to the survival of fish
and other marine lives.
</P>
<P>
China to Face Water Shortage by 2010
</P>
<P>
With a growing population and rapid economic development, China
is facing a water shortage that threatens to bottleneck its urban
development, experts with the Ministry of Water Resources said.
</P>
<P>
The country will experience its most serious water shortage
after 2010, they warned.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry statistics, China will need 698.8
billion cubic meters of water in 2010, while the water supply is
only 667 billion cubic meters, leaving a gap of 31.8 billion cubic
meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
