<HEADLINE> U.N. Group's Withdrawal From Zimbabwe not to Affect Commonwealth Group: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The withdrawal of the United
Nations group from Zimbabwe will not have any effect on the
Commonwealth Observer Group to monitor Zimbabwe's parliamentary
elections on June 24-25, Commonwealth group chairman Abdusalami
Abubakar said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar, former head of Nigeria, said he did not know anything
about the U.N. group's operations and its withdrawal would not
affect his group's operations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. group announced its pulling out of the election
process in Zimbabwe to international press on Friday, saying the
Zimbabwean government had rejected its offer to coordinate
international observers, and Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
had demoted the group to participate just as an observer group
monitoring the election.
</P>
<P>
"If we are not coordinating there is no reason for us to stay
there (Zimbabwe)," U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told an
international news agency.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after arriving in the country with his
team of 44 observers on Friday, Abubakar said his group was
constituted by, and would report to Commonwealth
Secretary-general Don Mckinon.
</P>
<P>
"Our mandate is to consider the various factors impinging on
the credibility of the electoral process as a whole and to
determine in our own judgement whether the condition exists for a
free expression of will by the electors and the results reflect
their wishes," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
