<HEADLINE> Jordan to Maintain Distinguished Ties With Syria: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 10 (Xinhua)-- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdel Rauf
Rawabdeh said Saturday that his country was keen to maintain what
he called distinguished ties with Syria after the passing away of
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
In a statement after an urgent cabinet session on the death of
Assad, Rawabdeh voiced confidence that the Syrian people will
overcome difficulties after the loss of Assad and to achieve his
unfulfilled goals.
</P>
<P>
Assad, 69, died of a heart attack earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh affirmed that Jordan will stand with Syria and keep the
distinguished ties with Syria after a new president comes to power
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein made a
phone call to Bashar al-Assad, the second and favorite son of
Assad, to express his condolences.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian parliament amended the constitution after Assad died
to lower the age threshold for a president from 40 to 34 to pave
the way for Bashar, 35, to become the new president.
</P>
<P>
Assad died at a time when Jordan and Syria are improving ties
after years of tensions over Jordan's 1994 peace treaty with
Israel. Assad had stood against any unilateral Arab peace deal with
Israel and had been at odds with late Jordanian King Hussein Ibn
Talal, King Abdullah's father, over the treaty.
</P>
<P>
However, Assad paid a surprising and fence-mending visit to
Amman, his first in years, in Febuary 1999 to attend the funeral of
Hussein who died of cancer.
</P>
<P>
The ties between the two countries thawed after the visit by
Assad.  
</P>
