<HEADLINE> Syrian People Deplore Assad's Death, Pledge Support to Bashar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Upon hearing the breaking news
that Syrian President Hafez al-Assad died of a heart attack
Saturday, the Syrian people poured into the streets of Damascus to
express their surprise, depression and grief over the loss of their
leader and their support to Bashar al-Assad, the new president
hopeful.
</P>
<P>
Shops closed their doors, verses of the holy Koran were recited
at mosques and church bells rang in grief over the death of the
Syrian leader, who served as the country's president for the past
three decades.
</P>
<P>
Security was beefed up, especially along the roads to the
presidential palace and Assad's residence in downtown Damascus,
when people swarmed into the capital from all over the country to
pay their last respect to Assad.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Syrian officials met to arrange for Assad's funeral
and to take the necessary decisions to secure a smooth transition
of power to Bashar, the second and favorite son of Assad. Those
measures are expected to be announced in the next few hours.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian parliament has amended the constitution to lower the
age threshold for a president from 40 to 34 to pave the way for
Bashar, 35, to become the new president.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian government has declared a 40-day official mourning
for Assad. However, the date for his funeral has not been declared
yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
