<HEADLINE> Arafat's Advisor Refutes Barak's Words on Final Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian official on Saturday
lashed out at a statement made by the Israeli prime minister that a
peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians could be
unlikely by September 13.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing Prime Minister Ehud Barak's remarks as "an attempt to
waste time," Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's advisor Nabil Abu-
Rudeina said they also sent a "non-positive indication" before the
two sides resume the final-status talks in Washington early next
week.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are opposed to putting off the final-status
talks, especially on the fate of Jerusalem, Abu-Rudeina told
reporters, pointing out that the signed accords between the two
sides involved a final peace agreement by September 13.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the U.S. administration to effectively step in to
stop further infringements by Israel, stressing that a just and
comprehensive peace needed an Israeli compliance with the
international resolutions and withdrawal of Israeli troops from all
territories it occupied in the l967 Middle East war, including
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Barak told reporters on Saturday that it could be unlikely to
reach the final peace agreement by the September 13 deadline,
disclosing that he instructed his negotiating team not to touch on
the issue of Jerusalem for the time being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
