<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Mkapa Chosen to Run for Second Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhang Dacheng
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian ruling Chama Cha
Mapinduzi (CCM) party chose on Saturday its chairman and Tanzanian
President Benjamin William Mkapa the sole presidential candidate
to run for his second five- year term in the October general
elections.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, aged 62, picked again Vice President Dr. Omar Ali Juma,
59, as his running mate, sources from the central town of Dodoma
said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, whose nomination was endorsed on Friday by the CCM
National Executive Committee (NEC), scooped 99.1 percent of votes
cast by some 1,200 delegates at an extraordinary congress of the
CCM in Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
"I am overwhelmed by the great love and confidence you have
bestowed on me," said the visibly moved president in the Chimwaga
hall, some six kilometers from Dodoma town. "I am at loss to know
how to repay you," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday the NEC also named Zanzibar Minister for
Communication and Transport Amani Abeid Karume as the CCM only
candidate for the Zanzibar presidency.
</P>
<P>
Karume, 52, is the eldest son of the late founding president of
Zanzibar following the 1964 revolution Abeid Amani Karume who led
Zanzibar until April 7, 1972 when he was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
Karume vowed following the voting that he would defend the
union between Zanzibar and the mainland at any cost and boost the
isles economic development if elected Zanzibar President.
</P>
<P>
The NEC further appointed Ambassador Seif Idd the CCM Deputy
Secretary General for Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the CCM congress also awarded the late founding
President of Tanzania Julius Kambarage Nyerere a medal called the
Great Leader of the 20th Century. Nyerere died of leukaemia in
London last October at the age of 77.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa presented a glittering gold medal to Nyerere's widow
Maria Nyerere, commending Nyerere's leadership qualities and his
contribution to Tanzania' s prosperity.
</P>
<P>
During the congress, the main streets of the Dodoma
Municipality was decorated with CCM flags and banners, which
permeated with a solemn atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement by Tanzania's National Electoral
Commission (NEC) on Thursday, a total of 12.5 million of the 30
million population are expected to vote in 232 constituencies
throughout the country in this year' s general elections.
</P>
<P>
The NEC on Tuesday issued a draft code of conduct for the
upcoming general elections, banning government and ruling party
leaders from using their power for political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
According to a timetable issued by the NEC early this year, the
 registration of voters will be conducted between August 1 and 21
while nomination of contestants will be made on August 13, and
election campaigns between August 14 and October 28.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania had been under a single political party (CCM) system
from 1965 until 1992 when the multiparty system was introduced.
</P>
<P>
The October elections will be the second time since 1995, but
the first time in the country's post-independence history for
presidential, parliamentary and civic elections to be held
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
All the 13 fully registered political parties run for the
elections which are likely to be dominated by the ruling CCM, at
least on the mainland as President Mkapa, who won the 1995
elections, is expected to win him the second five-year term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
