<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mafia's Drug War in Italy Leaves Two Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A violent ambush in Italy's southern
city of Naples Saturday evening which left two local mafiosi dead
and two others injured, including a 12-year-old child, was
probably part of a drug trafficking war between rival Camorra
clans, the local crime organizations, police said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The attack took place in the heart of the Naples, in the so-
called Spanish Quarter, when four or five men burst into a
basement where a party was taking place and opened fire, killing
Giuseppe Di Tommaso, 42, and critically injuring Luigi De Falco,
34, who died Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Another local criminal, Ciro Linardi, was hit in the leg, while
his 12-year-old niece was hit in the foot.
</P>
<P>
Police said that they were increasingly convinced that the
attack was to do with an on-going war between rival clans in the
Camorra, the Naples version of the Mafia, to gain control of the
local drug market.
</P>
<P>
A priest from the neighborhood told the Italian news agency
Ansa that they were all under shock. The shoot-out took place just
as mass was ending. A minute later they would have been firing
among the people as they were coming out of church.
</P>
<P>
There have been 49 Camorra-linked murders in and around Naples
since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
Just last week, four suspected Camorra members were shot dead
in four separate incidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000611.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Claims: Ethiopia's Offensive Foiled on Assab Front </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's large-scale offensive
on the Assab front in east Eritrea involving three divisions has
been totally foiled after more than 48 hours fighting, the
Eritrean Foreign Ministry said Sunday in a statement available
here.
</P>
<P>
"Ethiopian forces have been forced to retreat, with staggering
losses, to their original positions," the statement said, adding
that "fighting has subsided this morning apart from the odd
shelling."
</P>
<P>
The ministry did not give full details of Ethiopian loss on the
Assab front which "were not available."
</P>
<P>
The statement said the fighting in the western part of the
country continued all the day (Saturday) without any change in
the relative positions of both sides.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Eritrean forces recaptured the towns of
Tesseney, barentu, Haicota, Tekhombia, Awagaro and Guluj, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement said "Ethiopia has missed the OAU (the
 Organization of African Unity) deadline to pronounce
unequivocally its acceptance or rejection of the OAU proposal on
the cessation of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea said on Saturday that it had accepted the OAU proposal
for immediate cease-fire with its Horn of Africa neighbor
Ethiopia. The proposal was presented to the two countries during
their proximity talks in Algiers, Algeria, on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
